The paper proposes a deep learning approach for parallel MRI reconstruction, which involves image processing and computer vision techniques, suggesting that it belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of k-space sampling patterns, which are commonly used in signal processing and image analysis, indicating that it could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on time-resolved MR angiography, which is a medical imaging application, suggesting that it could belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of neural networks, which are a common tool in the field of neural engineering, indicating that it could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
